The paper presents a game-theoretic approach for distributed decision making in a robotic team, which involves coordination and cooperation among the robots. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Multiagent Systems (cs.MA) sub-category. Additionally, the paper uses a learning process to allow the robots to accomplish their objectives, which suggests that it could also belong to the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category. The problem being addressed involves control effort allocation in a robotic team, which suggests that the Robotics (cs.RO) sub-category is also likely. The approach presented involves interpreting action selection as an n-player cooperative game, which suggests that the Game Theory (cs.GT) sub-category is also relevant. Finally, the paper addresses the problem of making legal, safe, considerate, and empathetic decisions by robots, which suggests that the Systems and Control (cs.SY) sub-category is also relevant.
